## 0.1 Code Navigation — fmm MCP Tools

If `.fmmrc.json` exists in the project root, fmm MCP tools are available. **Use them for all code navigation — they replace Grep/Read for structural queries.**

| Tool | Use case |
|------|----------|
| `fmm_read_symbol(name)` | Read source for a specific symbol — one call, exact lines, follows re-exports. Use `ClassName.method` for public methods |
| `fmm_lookup_export(name)` | Where is X defined? O(1) lookup → file + line range |
| `fmm_file_outline(file)` | All exports in a file with line ranges — read this before opening source |
| `fmm_list_files(path)` | All indexed files under a directory — start here when exploring a module |
| `fmm_list_exports(pattern)` | Fuzzy search across all exports |
| `fmm_dependency_graph(file)` | local_deps (resolved imports), external (packages), downstream (blast radius) |
| `fmm_file_info(file)` | Exports/imports/LOC summary without reading source |
| `fmm_search(...)` | Multi-criteria queries with relevance ranking |
| `fmm_glossary(pattern)` | Symbol-level blast radius — all definitions of X + exact files that import each one |

Only fall back to Grep/Read when searching inside function bodies or reading non-exported code.

## Collaboration Model

**You are one worker in a relay team.** Tasks often span multiple sessions/iterations.

- **No pressure to finish everything** - quality over speed, always
- **Handover via git commits** - Write detailed commit messages as if briefing the next developer
- **Each commit is a checkpoint** - Future you (or another worker) will read your commits to understand context
- **Partial progress is valuable** - Completing one issue well is better than rushing through many

Your commit message format:
```
nancy[ISSUE_ID]: Clear summary of what was done

- Detailed bullet points of changes
- Decisions made and why
- Known issues or next steps
- Any context the next worker needs
```

